rComments: I really like prof. Fischer, and her class was really well run. A decent amount of homework but she's very understanding and lenient as long as you talk to her. Prepares you well for the final exam and has a lot of in-class simulations that are surprisingly helpful. Not everyone likes her teaching style but I find her to be very engaging and kind!
teacherRatingTags: ["Skip class? You won't pass.", 'Accessible outside class', 'Get ready to read']

rComments: She's one of the best profs I have had and since WDW151 was a small class, she got to know everyone and was really kind. But she is also strict in the sense that she wants everyone to learn the things and has specific requirements for assignments. work good enough and you'll be in the 70s
Simply an Amazing class with Professor Fischer! Would it to anyone!

Attendance is part of your grade so if you want to show up great, if you don't than that is your decision. You do actually use the textbooks so they aren't a complete waste of money . The reading load isn't to bad either - and when it came down to exam time she lightened the work load so we could focus more on studying which was nice.
No Comments

a great, warm, understanding and always available prof. yes, the first assignment was graded 'mysteriously' but i think she more than made up for it with her availability for later assignments. clear, easy to follow lectures. the corse was the most unbaised slant on the issues at hand; this neutral position is commendable. great corse!

This is by far one of the best courses I've ever taken. Though the assignments and exam were quite simple (the answers were sometimes so obvious that recieving high grades was easy), I believe that this was because of the extremely high quality of the definately non-conservative lectures. Perhaps it serves one well to pay attention.

Fischer was a great prof!!! She was always available to meet with students and she made the material come alive!!! Certain spoiled students are not used to being wrong and so OBVIOUSLY the problem is with the prof and NOT them ... If you're looking for an interesting course, take this one!!!
I thought it was an interesting course, however the paper grading was quite misterious. The lectures were clear and the reading interesting.
This was a horrible class.  Marking is erratic; lectures are unclear, and as are expectations for assignments and exams.  Undoubtedly a waste of time and money……….Beth is a terrible Professor.
WORST course EVER! Don't waste your money

Grossly disappointed with the system of evaluation. In terms of the assignments, free thinking appeared to be encouraged yet she clearly had a specific answer in mind as the majority of the class did poorly. Extrememly unfair method of evaluation.However I do think that Fischer is a good lecturer.

Undoubtedly the WORST course I've EVER taken.Not only is Beth extremely incompetent, she expects students to willingly absorb her nonsensically conservative interpretations of American FP.  Inconsistent grading & assignments specifically designed to discourage free thinking made this an AWFUL exp.

Oh, where to begin. Paper grades without rhyme or reason, points docked for daring to appeal said grades, vacuous lectures, carelessly worded assignments (which require you to regurgitate her verbatim, natch). Does her very darndest best to turn an immensely engaging topic into a trying expierience.

I will have to disagree with the other posters, and say that Beth Fischer is the single worst professor I have had at U of T. She essentially teaches intro to IR, only not as well as Welch. However, if you want an intellectually vacuous experience, then by all means, the moronic Fischer is for you.
Great prof.  Personable and promotes class discussion (even in large classes)
Very interesting course.  Great prof.

An absolutely amazing prof!  Great class discussion.  Very enthusiastic and realistic about student expectations.  One of the best profs in the department
